 1 would work for most apples, but breaks for apple 1 since there's no cumulative value of 0. I need a different approach.\n\nI can use COUNTIF instead: counting how many cumulative values are less than the apple index, then adding 1 gives me the correct month. Testing this logic—apple 1 gives month 1, apple 2 gives month 2, apple 6 gives month 2, and apple 7 gives month 3—it works consistently.\n\nNow I'm trying to understand what \"not present in apples accum row\" means. The cumulative row contains specific values like 1, 6, 7, 10, 12, and so on. If an apple index appears in that row, it's the last apple of that month. If it doesn't appear, it falls somewhere in the middle of a month. Let me re-read the original requirement to clarify what needs to happen in those cases.\n\nSo the formula should give a base month value, and then add 1 if the apple index isn't found in the cumulative row. Testing this logic with MATCH using approximate match: apple 1 matches exactly at position 1 (month 1, no adjustment needed), apple 2 doesn't match exactly so it gets bumped to month 2, apple 6 matches exactly at position 2 (month 2), and I need to check what happens with apple 7. Verifying the formula works across all test cases: Apple 1 correctly maps to month 1, while Apple 2-5 all map to month 2 since they're not in the accumulated range, and the pattern holds when checking Apple 6 at position 2.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":340,"cache_read_input_tokens":15577,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":340},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7c3359ad-1620-462f-8941-05f7b8b5c92e","uuid":"eab46e13-dbb9-4a46-9275-db49f427b3a4"}
